- input group has extra 2px, it should be 36px not 38px
- component's variables are incossistent, some of them use padding and the rest has padding-x and padding-y, and should really standardize this to make sure what to expose and tha naming too. for example, should we expose the vars like --x-bg-hover or &:hover { --x-bg: xxx; } (overriding the vars in state instead). also some components needs to expose more vars like placehodler color, input color, etc. the dashboard's input search class is a good example on variables are being too incosistent and need better approach
- why is there dropdown and dropdown-menu, shouldnt it be dropdown__menu instead?
- resizing sidebar is not pleasant. for example, in sidebar collapsed mode, most of the time the sidebar item button getting shrinked because of the root's padding. we might have to reduce the content padding when the root is collapsed
- still no 'standard' way to write custom css like adding extra modifier in a component like .card--stat
- popup like dropdown-menu could be have more elevating shadow
- for 'customized component' like a dropdown to become a 'message dropdown' where has list of user messages, while it works but i think it could be better. for example, is this good for u?
  .dropdown-menu--message {
  .item {
  --item-padding: calc(0.375rem _ var(--st-density))
  calc(0.75rem _ var(--st-density));
  --item-radius: var(--dropdown-item-radius);
  }
  }
- in the same customized component, the 'unread message' is having a different background like the accent bg, currently we can use data-state="active". while it works, but is it still considered as semantic?
- in real case, the .page will likely have an internal container. adding container to the .page will makes the container a direct flex item of the .page root instead of the .page__section. this will makes the .page__section losing their gaps.
- composition issue. is having .item as the dropdown-menu content condisedered semantic? and also, while it works, is composing .item.dropdown__item (for example) violating BEM or any rules?
- still about the variables. we shuold find a way to avoid something like this:
  .btn:not(.dropdown-menu .btn) {
    --btn-tone: var(--st-primary-foreground);
    &:hover {
      background-color: var(--navbar-button-hover-bg);
    }
  }
  i mean, the `:not()` select shouldnt be there in the first place. it could be about style leaking or about 'scoping' issue that tailwind users mourning about
- this has to be the significant issue. in real case, we will pretty much have to create custom components and writing custom css or css in general. for most people, writing css from scratch is nightmare and unpleasant experience. the issues would likely about the naming issue, style leaking (global override), scope, importance, and having to write padding: im-not-sure-yetpx; instead of px-4. im not gonna propose u to swap to tailwind. but we could make this better. the last issue, we could solve it by providing syntactic sugar, this could be happen by writing our 'tailwind-like' framework by in css, or other way that provide a better syntax with constraints. maybe something like:
  .something {
    // instead of
    backdrop-filter: blur(3px);

    // it could be just
    blur(3px);
    // or
    @blur: 3px;
    // or
    @padding-inline: loose; // 20px, `loose` is tshirt
  }
  that's just contrive example, the point is we could make the css writing experience is pleasant. this is just for the people who setting up the build process, like vite, react, or vue users.
- i drop the overflow: hidden; in the card, now the table's last row hover accent background isnt rounded. DONT USE the overflow hidden to fix this
- composition still an issue. for example, i want to drop the table last row border if it's in the table. with ~/ui/selia, i could write a utility to drop the border in the card classes. but, in stisla, i think this could be in the table css instead. so it should predict the common use cases of the table like i did in selia (feels right out of the box by predicting common composition use cases), some of the components already implemented this but still not yet enforced

footnote:
im start to think that we could employ tailwind again, but that would be much worse. for example, yes we could use tailwind's utilities to build something or to tweak components easily, but this will end up worse as the user will start creating custom components, and they will use tailwind utilities instead of creating new css file which turns out the design system will having two methodologies in a single project which not what we want it to be.

